     <physDesc>
      <p>Some later medieval comments in Latin appear in the margins of 65v. There are also a number of emendations and additions by the Tremulous Hand of Worcester.</p>
       <p>A single emendation on 66r appears, an insertion of 'ne' with a comma-shaped marking from below. This appears to be the work of either DP1032a or DP1032b, but the sample is small and the features of 'e' are not a clear match for either hand.</p>
       <handDesc>
       <handNote xml:id="DP1032" ana="Wulfgeat" ref="https://pase.ac.uk/jsp/DisplayPerson.jsp?personKey=101795" corresp="http://www.digipal.eu/digipal/hands/1032/"><p>Ker's scribe 'O'. The scribe Wulfgeat. A round Anglo-Saxon miniscule. A slight lean to the right. Round, unroofed a; a mixture of descending insular long s and tall s; round d with short ascender that usually has a small flick or curve to the upper-right at its tip. Ash is of oe-form, with o always somewhat smaller, sometimes with tall e. e is horned, with a short tongue and a squinting eye. Ascenders of tall letters are wedged, leaning towards forking; thorn is noticeably forked. a is quite rounded in form.</p></handNote>
      </handDesc>
